Implementation summary:
- The reader/writer pair is the wire-level foundation for the
  WebSocket transport stack (tasks 4.2–4.5). Both classes live
  in a new Transport/WebSocket/ folder under the existing Core
  asmdef so they share the project's nullable-enable / langver
  10 surface.
- The reader implements all five mandated opcodes (Text 0x1,
  Continuation 0x0, Close 0x8, Ping 0x9, Pong 0xA) plus Binary
  0x2 (parsed but the higher-level transport will reject it per
  design.md §WebSocketServer "非サポート: Binary"). Direction-
  specific masking enforcement is encoded by the requireMask
  ctor argument so the same class serves both server and client
  read paths.
- The accumulated 1 MB ceiling is enforced both at the single-
  frame layer (Req 3.10 — drop oversized frame) and at the
  multi-fragment assembly layer (Req 3.10 — close 1009 will be
  emitted by WebSocketServer in task 4.3 once the reader reports
  MessageTooBig). UTF-8 validation runs on the assembled Text
  message so that mid-fragment partial code points are not
  spuriously rejected; close 1007 emission lives in the future
  WebSocketServer.
- The writer's masking key is injected via Func<uint> so the
  EditMode tests get byte-stable output. Production code passes
  no provider and gets the cryptographic
  RandomNumberGenerator.Create() default. Concurrent writes are
  serialised by a SemaphoreSlim — required because each
  IClientConnection will share one writer between the inbound
  request handler and the outbound publish path.
- No Unity engine references, no PlayerLoop coupling — the
  whole module is unit-testable in EditMode against
  MemoryStream, which is exactly what the spec calls for ("RFC
  6455 §5 の主要ケースを網羅する Editor テスト").

